<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06087042 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06087042 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  STOCK; INVESTMENT; GUIDELINE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  Building a stock portfolio is a complex, time-consuming, inconvenient process,even for the most savvy investors.;    Because of that, many investors havedecided to let someone else build a portfolio for them. The result has been aboom in the mutual-fund business.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Business  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  HERE'S A BEGINNER'S GUIDE TO BUYING MUTUALFUNDS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     Mutual funds, in many ways, are like giant investment clubs.;    They havebeen around since the 1920s, but really came into vogue in the mid-1980s.;   Mutual funds manage more than 58 million customer accounts nationwide, valuedat more than $1 trillion, according to The Investment Company Institute, anindustry trade group. Some funds manage more than $1 billion in assets.;   But it is not the bigness of the funds that makes them appealing.;   Diversification and professional management are the lure.;    Funds invest ina wide range of securities; this diversity guards against &quot;betting it all&quot; onone issue. Many investors cannot afford a diversified portfolio.;    Operatedby investment companies, mutual funds are designed to pool the money ofinvestors with common financial goals.;    While some funds are sold bybrokers and charge a commission or sales fee to open an account, many others-- called &quot;no-load funds&quot; -- take no payment from shareholders.;    Some fundsallow individuals to open an account with as little as $50.;    But while itis easy to see the benefits of diversity and professional management, pickingthe right fund is not always so simple.;    Considering a mutual-fundinvestment is like going to a Baskin-Robbins ice cream shop -- except thereare more than 31 flavors to choose from.;    As a result, being satisfied witha fund requires understanding its investment goal.;    For example, a retiredcouple looking for stability and minimal risk would be out of place in anaggressive growth fund.;    The leading personal-finance magazines --particularly Changing Times and Money -- routinely review top-performingmutual funds, including vital information about investment returns, objectivesand where to call for an prospectus.;    The explosion in types of funds makesthe mutual fund tables in the newspaper more difficult to read, as a family offunds might have a &quot;high-quality fund&quot; investing in top-rated corporate andmunicipal securities and &quot;high-yield fund&quot; investing in junk bonds.;   Investors should always read a fund's prospectus to determine its goals beforeinvesting.;    Here is a taster's guide to 10 different flavors of mutualfund:;    (check) Growth funds invest in small companies that pay little or nodividends. Investors expect their capital to appreciate as the companies growand their stock prices rise.;    (check) Income funds accumulate high-gradecorporate bonds, as well as stocks with a long history of paying dividends.Investors often choose an income fund for its current dividend prospects,rather than their future appreciation potential.;    (check) Balanced fundsgenerally try to balance three primary investment objectives: income, growthand stability.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  The Allentown Morning Call  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Street  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910327  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  March  </MONTH><PG.COL>  7F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  471  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday March 27, 199100087042,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>